1. Model for the group median data

Read data

library(MASS)

data_median = read.table("https://zhanglj37.github.io/share/rm_pre/data_median.txt", header = TRUE)
attach(data_median)
head(data_median)
##        Days Value
## 1    1.0000  0.96
## 2    7.0000  0.88
## 3   30.4375  0.74
## 4  182.6250  0.48
## 5  365.0000  0.34
## 6 1825.0000  0.16

Conduct model

\[\begin{array}{c} Equation 1: V = A/(1 + k*D) \\Equation 2: V = A*e^{(-k*D)} \\Eqution 3: V = A/(1+k*D)^s \\Eqution 4: V = A/(1+k*D^s) \\Note: V: Value, A = 1, D: Days. \end{array}\] 
eq1.st <- c(k = 0)
eq1 <- nls(Value ~ 1/(1 + k*Days), start = eq1.st)

eq2.st <- c(k = 0)
eq2 <- nls(Value ~ 1*exp(-k*Days), data = data_median, 
    start = eq2.st)

eq3.st <- c(k = 0.1, s = 1) # try other initial values:k=0,1
eq3 <- nls(Value ~ 1/((1 + k*Days)^s), start = eq3.st)

eq4.st <- c(k = 0.1, s = 1) 
eq4 <- nls(Value ~ 1/(1 + k*(Days)^s), start = eq4.st)
  • try other initial value in eq3
eq3.st2 <- c(k = 0, s = 1) 
eq3_2 <- try(nls(Value ~ 1/((1 + k*Days)^s), start = eq3.st2))
## Error in nlsModel(formula, mf, start, wts) : 
##   singular gradient matrix at initial parameter estimates

How to debug: try other initial values or see the StackExchange

Plot

eq1.formula = y ~ 1/(1 + k*(x))
eq2.formula = y ~ 1*exp(-k*x)
eq3.formula = y ~ 1/((1 + k*x)^s)
eq4.formula = y ~ 1/(1 + k*(x)^s)

#install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
## Registered S3 methods overwritten by 'ggplot2':
##   method         from 
##   [.quosures     rlang
##   c.quosures     rlang
##   print.quosures rlang
ggplot(data = data_median, aes(Days,Value)) +
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "nls", 
              method.args = list(formula = eq1.formula,
                                 start = eq1.st), 
              data = data_median,
              se = FALSE,
              colour = "red")+
    geom_smooth(method = "nls", 
              method.args = list(formula = eq2.formula,
                                 start = eq2.st), 
              data = data_median,
              se = FALSE,
              colour = "blue")+
    geom_smooth(method = "nls", 
              method.args = list(formula = eq3.formula,
                                 start = eq3.st), 
              data = data_median,
              se = FALSE,
              colour = "orange")+
    geom_smooth(method = "nls", 
              method.args = list(formula = eq4.formula,
                                 start = eq4.st), 
              data = data_median,
              se = FALSE,
              colour = "grey")+
    labs(caption = paste0("Red: Value = 1/(1+", round(coef(eq1),3), "*Days)\n",
                "Blue: Value = 1*exp(-", round(coef(eq3),3), "*Days)\n",
                "Orange: Value = 1/((1 + ", round(coef(eq3)[1],3), "*Days)^", round(coef(eq3)[2],3), ")\n",
                "Grey: Value = 1/(1 + ", round(coef(eq4)[1],3), "*(Days^", round(coef(eq4)[2],3), "))\n"))

2. Model for individuals

Read data

#install.packages("minpack.lm")
library(minpack.lm)
## Warning: package 'minpack.lm' was built under R version 3.6.3
library(MASS)

data_median = read.table("https://zhanglj37.github.io/share/rm_pre/data_median.txt", header = TRUE)
data_id = read.table("https://zhanglj37.github.io/share/rm_pre/data_id.txt", header = TRUE)
head(data_id)
##      ID delay1d delay7d delay1m delay6m delay1y delay5y delay25y
## 1 jh001    0.96    0.68    0.48    0.36    0.28    0.28     0.16
## 2 jh002    0.68    0.68    0.16    0.08    0.04    0.04     0.08
## 3 jh003    0.96    0.96    0.92    0.80    0.40    0.04     0.04
## 4 jh004    0.96    0.96    0.96    0.92    0.88    0.88     0.68
## 5 jh005    0.96    0.96    0.96    0.96    0.80    0.28     0.04
## 6 jh006    0.96    0.96    0.92    0.72    0.44    0.24     0.04
N = dim(data_id)[1]
Days = data_median$Days

Conduct model

rsquare = estk = array(0, dim = c(N, 4)) # save r-square and k estimates for each individual
ests = ests_p = array(0, dim = c(N, 2)) # save s estimates for each individual

for (i in 1:N)
{
    # define a new dataset for participant i
    data_temp = rbind(data_id[i, 2:8], Days)
    data_temp = data.frame(t(data_temp))
    colnames(data_temp) = c("Value", "Days")
    
    # set the max number of interations in nls(), the default value is 50
    nlc <- nls.control(maxiter = 1000)

    # modeling
    eq1.st <- c(k = 0)
    eq1 <- nls(Value ~ 1/(1 + k*Days), 
        data = data_temp, start = eq1.st)
    eq2.st <- c(k = 0)
    eq2 <- nls(Value ~ 1*exp(-k*Days), data = data_temp, 
        start = eq2.st) 
    eq3.st <- c(k = 0.1, s = 1)
    eq3 <- nlsLM(Value ~ 1/((1 + k*Days)^s), data = data_temp, 
       start = eq3.st, control = nlc)   
       # nlsLM is a modified version of nls that uses Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm. 
       # reference: John C.N. (2014). Nonlinear Parameter Optimization Using R Tools.
    eq4.st <- c(k = 0.1, s = 1) 
    eq4 <- nls(Value ~ 1/(1 + k*(Days)^s), data = data_temp, 
       start = eq4.st, control = nlc)

    # save results for each participant
    for (j in 1:4)
    {
        estk[i,j] = coef(get(paste0("eq",j)))[1] # k, when j = 1, coef(eq1)
        rsquare[i,j] = (cor(data_temp$Value,predict(get(paste0("eq",j)))))^2
        
        if (j > 2)
        {
            ests[i,j-2] = coef(get(paste0("eq",j)))[2] # s
            ests_p[i,j-2] = coef(summary(get(paste0("eq",j))))[2,4] # p value for s
        }
    }   
}

Convergence problem

Conduct model

rsquare = estk = array(0, dim = c(N, 4)) # save r-square and k estimates for each individual
ests = ests_p = array(0, dim = c(N, 2)) # save s estimates for each individual
error_id = 0
k = 1
for (i in 1:N)
{
    # define a new dataset for participant i
    data_temp = rbind(data_id[i, 2:8], Days)
    data_temp = data.frame(t(data_temp))
    colnames(data_temp) = c("Value", "Days")
    
    # set the max number of interations in nls(), the default value is 50
    nlc <- nls.control(maxiter = 1000)

    # modeling
    eq1.st <- c(k = 0)
    eq1 <- nls(Value ~ 1/(1 + k*Days), 
        data = data_temp, start = eq1.st)
    eq2.st <- c(k = 0)
    eq2 <- nls(Value ~ 1*exp(-k*Days), data = data_temp, 
        start = eq2.st) 
    eq3.st <- c(k = 0.1, s = 1)
    eq3 <- try(nls(Value ~ 1/((1 + k*Days)^s), data = data_temp, 
        start = eq3.st, control = nlc))

    eq4.st <- c(k = 0.1, s = 1) 
    eq4 <- nls(Value ~ 1/(1 + k*(Days)^s), data = data_temp, 
       start = eq4.st, control = nlc)




    if("try-error" %in% class(eq3))
    {
        error_id[k] = i
        k = k + 1
        for (j in c(1,2,4))
        {
            estk[i,j] = coef(get(paste0("eq",j)))[1] # k, when j = 1, coef(eq1)
            rsquare[i,j] = (cor(data_temp$Value,predict(get(paste0("eq",j)))))^2
            
            if (j > 2)
            {
                ests[i,j-2] = coef(get(paste0("eq",j)))[2] # s
                ests_p[i,j-2] = coef(summary(get(paste0("eq",j))))[2,4] # p value for s
            }
        }
    }else{
        # save results for each participant
        for (j in 1:4)
        {
            estk[i,j] = coef(get(paste0("eq",j)))[1] # k, when j = 1, coef(eq1)
            rsquare[i,j] = (cor(data_temp$Value,predict(get(paste0("eq",j)))))^2
            
            if (j > 2)
            {
                ests[i,j-2] = coef(get(paste0("eq",j)))[2] # s
                ests_p[i,j-2] = coef(summary(get(paste0("eq",j))))[2,4] # p value for s
            }
        }
    
    }
    
}

Plot

convergence = rep(1,N)
convergence[error_id] = 0

plot (x = Days, y = data_median$Value, ylab = "Value")
for (i in 1:15)
{
    if (convergence[i] == 1)
    {
        color = "red"
    }else{
        color = "blue"
    }
    lines(x = Days, y = data_id[i, 2:8], col = color)

}
